Problem 1

Look at the following histogram and answer the questions.

  1. What is the proportion of values in the sample that exceed \(5\)? Explain your answer. We have \(1+10+4=15\) elements less than \(5\) and \(4+1=5\) elements greater than \(5\). Therefore, \(5/20=0.25\) of elements exceed \(5\).
  2. Indicate the interval where the median of this sample can lie. Explain your answer. We can see that \(1+10=11\) elements are less than \(0\), while \(4+4+1=9\) elements are greater than \(0\). Combined with the knowledge from the previous question, we can say that the median lies between \(0\) and \(5\).
  3. How the histogram will change if we add an element \(7\) to the sample? Explain your answer. The bin corresponding to the interval between \(5\) and \(10\) will become slightly higher (there will now be \(5\) elements inside this interval).

Problem 2

  1. Look at the histograms of two samples. They illustrate the distribution of normalized average reaction time to frequent words (in ms) in two groups of people.

Which of the samples has a larger variance? Explain your answer. In the sample2, all the elements lie between \(400\) and \(600\), while in the sample1, there are elements outside this interval. Therefore, sample1 has a larger variance.

Which of the samples has a larger variance? Explain your answer. In the sample1, all the elements lie roughly between \(-10\) and \(10\), while in the sample2, the elements lie roughly between \(8\) and \(12\). Sample1 has a larger variance.

Problem 3

Below is the histogram of the number of mistakes students made while writing an examination essay in English. Look at the histogram and answer the questions.

3.1

Is it true that \(50\)% students made more than \(35\) mistakes?

NO

Explain your answer below: There are clearly more elements between \(0\) and \(35\).

3.2

Is it true that most students made no more than \(10\) mistakes?

NO

Explain your answer below: The combined area of the bins for values that exceed \(10\) is clearly greater.

3.3

Which of the following values is closer to be the median of mistakes: \(10\), \(20\), \(30\), \(40\)?

20

Explain your answer below: The bins are higher in the interval between \(0\) and \(20\), but there are more bins for values that exceed \(20\). As a result, the two parts are close to being equal by the overall area.

Problem 4. Exact binomial test

The null hypothesis is that \(p=0\) (i.e.no success is possible). In a dataset, there is only one success out of 1 000 000 observations. Will you reject the null hypothesis?

YES

Explain your answer below: If we accept the null hypothesis, no matter how many times we observe the situation, there must absolutely never be a success. The fact that it happened just once is enough to reject the null hypothesis with absolute certainty.

Problem 7. Position of verbs in verses

The dataset The last words in verses is based on texts written in the 1820s and 1920s (Corpus of Russian Poetry of the Russian National Corpus). Authors collected only one line per author to keep observations as independent from each other as possible.

Variables:
- Decade decade of creation: 1820s, 1920s.
- RhymedNwords the number of words in the rhyming position (usually one word, but there are two words in cases such as (I would like to get) wine (which is rhymed with toad, see http://russian-poetry.ru/Poem.php?PoemId=18261)).
- RhymedNsyl the number of syllables in the rhyming position.
- UPoS part of speech of the last word. - LineText a sampled verse.
- Author the author of the text.

Can we decide that in verses written in 1920s, verbs in the rhyming posision are used differently (more often or less often) than expected for verbs in general?

Lets assume that the probability for verbs to be used in any position (in general) is 17% (according to ).

7.1 State hypothesis

What is your null hypothesis \(H_0\) and what is the alternative hypothesis \(H_1\)?

H0: P(UPoS="VERB") = 0.17
H1: P(UPoS="VERB") != 0.17

7.2

Read the dataset The last words in verses. Filter out the relevant observations from 1920s, calculate the number of verbs observed in the sample, and the sample size.

library(tidyverse)
## Warning in as.POSIXlt.POSIXct(Sys.time()): unknown timezone 'zone/tz/2019c.1.0/

data_1920s <- data[data$Decade == '1920s',] %>% select(-Decade)
n_examples <- nrow(data_1920s)
n_examples
## [1] 277
n_verbs <- nrow(data_1920s[data_1920s$UPoS == 'VERB',])
n_verbs
## [1] 39

7.3

Use an exact binomial test to calculate p-value.

binom.test(n_verbs, n_examples, p=0.17)
## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  n_verbs and n_examples
## number of successes = 39, number of trials = 277, p-value = 0.2297
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.17
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1020719 0.1874081
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##              0.1407942

7.4 Interpret results

Give your interpretation of obtained p-value. Answer the initial question: Can we decide that in verses written in 1920s, verbs are used in the rhyming posision more often or less often than expected?

The obtained p-value is not small enough to reject the null hypothesis. We cannot say conclusively whether in verses written in the 1920s, verbs were used in the rhyming position more or less often than in any other position.

Write down your general conlusions about data provided for both 1920s and 1820s data.

For the 1820s, the p-value is rather big, almost but not quite big enough for us to conclude that the null hypothesis is, in fact, correct.
We cannot say with any sufficient level of certainty that verbs were used more or less often in the rhyming position than in any other, neither for the 1820s nor for the 1920s.

Problem 8. One-sample t-test

Using Icelandic data on vowel duration from seminar Link test the null hypothesis that the population mean of vowel duration in speaker shg05 equals 73 (ms). To perform a one-sample t-test, you can use the following example of R code:

t.test(sample, mu = 7725) # mu is a population mean

8.1

Write down a two-tailed alternative hypothesis.

H1: vowel.dur(shg05) != 73 (ms)

8.2

Perform a one-sample t-test.

data <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/LingData2019/LingData2020/master/data/icelandic.csv')
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_character(),
##   index = col_double(),
##   time = col_double(),
##   word.dur = col_double(),
##   voicing.dur = col_double(),
##   vowel.dur = col_double(),
##   cluster.dur = col_double(),
##   spreading.dur = col_double(),
##   sonorant.dur = col_double(),
##   closure.dur = col_double(),
##   vor = col_double(),
##   voffr = col_double(),
##   mor = col_double(),
##   cond_no = col_double()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
data_shg05 <- data[data$speaker == 'shg05', ]
t.test(data_shg05$vowel.dur, mu=73)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data_shg05$vowel.dur
## t = -1.9602, df = 159, p-value = 0.05172
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 73
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  67.18817 73.02188
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  70.10502

8.3

Interpret results.

The observed p-value is 0.05172. It is not small enough to assert with 95% confidence that mean vowel duration in speaker shg05 does not equal 73 ms, but it is small enough to say that with 90% confidence.

Supplementary reading

Use of exact binomial test in lingiistic research:

  • Gries, Stefan Th. Phonological similarity in multi-word units. Cognitive Linguistics 22.3 (2011): 491-510. Link
    Stefan Gries proves that alliteration is observed in multi-word expressions more often than in general.

  • Harald Bayen (2008: 51-52) evaluates the probability of observing exactly one occurrence of the word hare in the corpus sample of 1 mln words given its estimated frequency of 8.23 words per million according to the SELEX frequency database.

On measures of central tendency:

  • Levshina 2015, Chapter 3 (p.48); Gries 2009, Chapter 1.3 (p.116).

On t-test:

  • Gries 2009, Chapter 3 (p.198).
